data.content:
Yes — MSTest 3.8+ introduced **generic `DynamicData`** attributes that give you compile-time type safety by eliminating the `object[]` boxing:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData<string, bool>(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string, bool)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**What changed:**
- `[DynamicData]` → `[DynamicData<string, bool>]` — generic type params match the test method signature
- `IEnumerable<object[]>` → `IEnumerable<(string, bool)>` — tuples instead of object arrays
- Array syntax `["x", true]` → tuple syntax `("x", true)`

This catches type mismatches at compile time rather than at test runtime. Requires **MSTest 3.8+** (`MSTest.TestFramework` NuGet package).
